// Common targets: svchost pipe reconnects, COM server named pipes, WCF endpoints`}]},{id:"mal-escape-alpc-squatting",title:"ALPC Port Squatting for Privilege Escalation",subtitle:"Race condition in ALPC connection establishment allows intercepting privileged service connections pre-initialization",tags:["ALPC","Advanced Local Procedure Call","port squatting","race condition","LPC","kernel IPC"],accentColor:"pink",overview:"ALPC (Advanced Local Procedure Call) is the Windows kernel IPC mechanism used by every local RPC call, COM object, and many system services. ALPC port names are registered in the NT object namespace. A race condition exists during service startup: if an attacker can create an ALPC port with the same name BEFORE the legitimate service registers it, subsequent connection attempts by clients will reach the attacker's port instead of the legitimate service. The attacker can then impersonate connecting clients, including privileged callers.",steps:["Monitor ALPC port registration using ETW (Microsoft-Windows-Kernel-File and Microsoft-Windows-ALPC providers)","Identify target services with predictable ALPC port names that are briefly unregistered during restart","Race the service restart: trigger a service restart via a recoverable error, then immediately register the port name","Accept connections and impersonate: ALPC does not require clients to specify a server SID by default — no authentication","Extract security token from connecting client via NtAlpcImpersonateClientOfPort or NtAlpcOpenSenderProcess"],commands:[{title:"ALPC port monitoring and squatting",code:`// Monitor ALPC port registrations with ETW
