// Tools: TokenViewer (James Forshaw), HandleExplorer, LeakedHandleFinder`}]},{id:"mal-escape-com-activation-hijack",title:"COM Server Activation Hijacking via DCOM SCM Race",subtitle:"Race the Service Control Manager during COM server activation to redirect DCOM object instantiation to attacker-controlled binary",tags:["COM hijack","DCOM","SCM race","activation hijack","InprocServer32","LocalServer32","COM marshal"],accentColor:"pink",overview:"When a COM server is activated via DCOM, the Service Control Manager (SCM) performs a series of registry lookups to locate the COM server binary. A race condition exists: between the SCM reading the registry key and launching the binary, a writable path in the executable location allows swapping the binary. More reliably, per-user COM server registration (HKCU\\Software\\Classes\\CLSID) takes precedence over per-machine (HKLM) — any user can hijack DCOM activations from privileged callers by pre-registering in HKCU.",steps:["Identify COM servers activated by privileged processes: ProcMon DCOM activation events, or enumerate InprocServer32/LocalServer32 under HKLM CLSIDs","Check if a per-user override in HKCU\\Software\\Classes\\CLSID\\{CLSID} is checked first — Windows checks HKCU before HKLM for many COM lookups","Register malicious LocalServer32 or InprocServer32 in HKCU pointing to your DLL/EXE","Wait for a privileged process to activate the COM object — your binary loads in the privileged context","For UAC bypass: many COM objects with auto-elevation (manifest IAccessible attribute) check HKCU first — register there for no-prompt elevation",'Enumerate auto-elevation CLSIDs: search HKLM CLSID registry for "Elevation" + "Enabled"="1" keys'],commands:[{title:"COM server hijacking via HKCU registry",code:`# Find COM objects activated by privileged processes
